# fs2chat-client is the **FS2 (Functional Streams for
# Scala) Chat Client** — example chat application
# demonstrating fs2 + cats-effect streaming patterns,
# from the typelevel ecosystem.  Pivots from Kotlin
# clikt (R277 svg2vd) into the **Scala language
# tooling cluster**.  Sister to fs2chat-server (same
# repo).  **MAJOR MILESTONE**: corpus's **first
# documented Scala CLI** AND first use of the **decline
# + cats-effect** ecosystem — adds Scala to the cross-
# language CLI taxonomy (17 library variants now).
#
# Critical extraction note: fs2chat-client uses
# **Scala's `decline`** library at `com.monovore.decline`
# — corpus's **first documented Scala CLI** AND first
# use of the **decline ecosystem**.  decline is a
# popular modern Scala CLI library built on
# **Applicative functors** (similar conceptually to
# Haskell's optparse-applicative R270 and OCaml's
# Cmdliner R271, but with Scala's cats typeclass
# library underneath).  Plus integrates with
# `cats-effect` for `IO`-based main fns.  Extends the
# **cross-language CLI taxonomy** to SEVENTEEN library
# variants (R276 added Java picocli; R277 added Kotlin
# clikt; R278 adds Scala decline): Rust (6: clap
# derive/builder/v3/hand-rolled/pico_args/lexopt), Go
# (4: cobra/pflag/flaggy/stdlib flag), Python (3:
# Click/argparse/Typer), Crystal OptionParser (R269),
# Haskell optparse-applicative (R270), OCaml Cmdliner
# (R271), C POSIX getopt (R272), Java picocli (R276),
# Kotlin clikt (R277), **Scala decline** (R278 — NEW).
# **JVM-language CLI trio now COMPLETE**: Java picocli
# (annotations) + Kotlin clikt (by-delegation) + Scala
# decline (applicative-functor with cats).  Documents
# the **3 JVM-language CLI declaration styles**: (a)
# Java picocli `@Annotation` + runtime reflection
# (R276 checkstyle), (b) Kotlin clikt `by`-delegation
# + chained DSL (R277 svg2vd), (c) Scala decline
# `Command + Opts.mapN` typeclass-composition (R278
# fs2chat-client).
#
# Critical extraction note: fs2chat-client uses
# **applicative-functor composition via `mapN`** at
# ClientApp.scala:11-28 — cats's `mapN` method on a
# tuple of Opts:
# ```
#   (
#     Opts.option[String]("username", "Desired username", "u")
#       .map(Username.apply),
#     Opts.option[String]("address", "Address of chat server")
#       .withDefault("127.0.0.1")
#       .mapValidated(p => IpAddress.fromString(p).toValidNel(...)),
#     Opts.option[Int]("port", "Port of chat server")
#       .withDefault(5555)
#       .mapValidated(p => Port.fromInt(p).toValidNel(...))
#   ).mapN { case (desiredUsername, ip, port) =>
#     desiredUsername -> SocketAddress(ip, port)
#   }
# ```
# `(opt1, opt2, opt3).mapN { ... }` is **applicative
# composition** — the tuple syntax uses cats's tuple-
# of-Opts → Opts of tuple lifting.  `mapN` then unwraps
# the parsed values and applies the combining function.
# Documents the **Scala applicative-functor CLI
# composition** — distinct from Haskell's `<$> <*>`
# (R270 carp) and OCaml's `let+ ... and+` (R271 dune)
# in SURFACE syntax but IDENTICAL in semantics.  All
# three are applicative-functor patterns.  Documents
# the **applicative-functor pattern in 3 languages**
# now: Haskell (`<$> / <*>`), OCaml (`let+ / and+`),
# Scala (`(.., ..).mapN { .. }`).  Corpus's **first
# documented Scala mapN applicative pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: fs2chat-client uses
# **`Opts.option[T](longName, help, shortName)`** at
# ClientApp.scala:13-15 — decline's typed option API.
# `Opts.option[String]("username", "Desired username",
# "u")` declares a `--username` option (and `-u` short)
# returning a `String`.  The TYPE PARAMETER `[String]`
# determines the parse type; decline auto-derives a
# `from-string` parser based on the type.  Documents
# the **type-parameter-driven option declaration** —
# distinct from clap derive's struct-field type
# auto-detection (R260 dua) and from Click's `type=int`
# kwarg (R266 uvicorn).  Scala's approach uses the
# type system explicitly: `Opts.option[Int]("port",
# ...)` for an Int, `Opts.option[String]` for a String,
# etc.  Compile-time type checking ensures the parsed
# value matches.
#
# Critical extraction note: fs2chat-client uses
# **`.mapValidated(p => X.fromString(p).toValidNel("...
# error..."))`** at ClientApp.scala:18 + 22 —
# decline's validation API returning `ValidatedNel[
# String, T]`.  ValidatedNel (Validated with NonEmpty
# List of errors) accumulates errors across multiple
# options (unlike Either which short-circuits on first
# error).  Useful when you want to report ALL invalid
# options at once rather than one at a time.  Documents
# the **ValidatedNel error-accumulation pattern** —
# distinct from clap derive's Result-style first-error
# bail (R248 cairo-coverage `anyhow::ensure!`) and
# from R273 irust's manual unknown_args warnings.
# Corpus's **first documented ValidatedNel error
# accumulation**.
